	<tr>
		
			<td colspan="2" bgcolor="#DEDACB" background="http://www.everlore.com/gimages/tb_beige.gif">
		
				<font face="verdana" size="2" color="black">
				Well, I've been away from this board for awhile and just read all the new posts. I'm still amazed to see people saying that going above 14 weight doesn't<BR>
matter. This may be true at low levels, when perhaps the AC bonus from leather helps, but I'm now a monk of level 30, and I can tell you that when you young<BR>
ones get older, you will fight hard to stay under 14. My AC drops nearly 10 pts when I go from 14 weight to 15. And if I hit 20 weight, my AC drops catastrophically. This is simply fact.<BR>
As for money, don't believe those who say you don't  need it. You don't need as much money as a cleric, but when you reach higher levels, you'll want some <BR>
nice jewelry, and it AIN'T cheap. I've got 2 serpentine bracers (9 agi, and 3 dex!!!!--very nice jewelry), and they<BR>
go for around 500 to 600 plat each!!!. So money matters, you better believe it.<BR>
As for stats, I've learned alot lately. With my 2 serpentine bracers, my Agi is now quite high, as you might imagine. I definitely get hit ALOT less, and <BR>
dodge, block more. This is sweet. But I feel I have neglected str and dex. I don't hit as often as I'd like, so I want some dex items. And I think if I could get my str up by about 10 pts, I'd do alot more damage, especially combined with the increased dex. I think I can achieve this goal by trading in my cheap<BR>
agi +2 or +3 rings and earrings for heavy-duty (and VERY VERY costly) jewelry that adds to str and dex.<BR>
I can do that without losing much of my agility bonuses and then I will be just about perfect. My point in this<BR>
long tirade on stats is that when starting out a new monk, it probably doesn't matter much what you put<BR>
your points into, since you will want lots more points from jewelry items when you get older anyway. Best would be to put them all into agility, and then<BR>
get yourself 2 serpentine bracers which will be all the agility you'll ever need, and then use earrings and rings for str and dex items. You then will have the necklace slot free for whatever stats you feel you want to increase further (I have a necklace with agi 6<BR>
and stamina 9!!!!--it was painfully expensive too) So yeah, save that money. When you get to higher levels, the groups you are in will notice whether you<BR>
are a good monk or a bad monk. Higher level players are more savvy and know the difference. So you'll want this jewelry, trust me. Good luck brother monks.<BR>
<BR>

				</font>
			</td>

	</tr>
	
